# Light / Dark Mode Text Contrast

## Rules

- **Light mode** → solid black text (`#17101f` or darker) on light card.
- **Dark mode** → solid white/cream text (`#fef9f0` or lighter) on dark card.
- Labels use `opacity: 0.72` for hierarchy — never `rgba()` with the same hue as the bg.
- Never rely on inherited `color` for the number/heading — set it explicitly.

## The lightningcss minifier bug

`lightningcss` (Vite's default minifier) **strips `[data-theme='light']` /
`[data-theme='dark']` from selectors that share a class with the base rule**.
Example — these get merged into one `.stat { ... }` rule and the dark one
wins for all themes:

```css
/* SOURCE — looks correct */
.stat { background: var(--bg); color: var(--text); }
[data-theme='light'] .stat { background: #fff; color: #000; }
[data-theme='dark']  .stat { background: #000; color: #fff; }
```

```css
/* BUILT — attribute selectors stripped, dark wins everywhere */
.stat { background: #000; color: #fff; }
```

## The fix: scope theme variables to a parent

Set theme-dependent colors as **CSS custom properties on a parent element**
that does NOT share a class with the children. Children reference the
variables. The minifier can't strip a `--var:` assignment.

```css
/* Parent — different class, minifier keeps the theme selectors */
.stat-grid {
  --stat-bg: var(--cosmic-ink);
  --stat-text: var(--cosmic-bg);
}

[data-theme='light'] .stat-grid {
  --stat-bg: #f7e6c8;   /* warm cream */
  --stat-text: #17101f; /* solid black */
}

[data-theme='dark'] .stat-grid {
  --stat-bg: #fef9f0;   /* cream */
  --stat-text: #0a0612; /* near-black */
}

/* Children — use the variables, no theme selectors needed */
.stat {
  background: var(--stat-bg);
  color: var(--stat-text);
}
.stat strong { color: var(--stat-text); }
.stat span   { color: var(--stat-text); opacity: 0.72; }
```

## Why this works

1. Theme selectors target `.stat-grid`, a different class from `.stat`, so
   lightningcss can't dedupe them with the base rule.
2. Children inherit the variables — no per-theme overrides needed on them.
3. The base rule can still use `var(--cosmic-ink)` as a fallback for
   components rendered before the theme attribute is set.
